  "relevant_summary": "Hole habitats (>50 mm) and pit habitats (1-50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures both support biodiversity, but there are key differences in their effects. Hole habitats have been studied less extensively (5 studies) compared to pit habitats (22 studies). Both habitat types can support species absent from structure surfaces without added features, with hole habitats supporting macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate species while pit habitats support macroalgae, invertebrate, and fish species.\n\nFor richness and diversity, hole habitats consistently increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species diversity/richness in all 3 studies that examined this effect. Pit habitats showed more variable results with 8 of 12 studies finding increased species richness/diversity, while others found no effect or mixed effects depending on site conditions.\n\nRegarding abundance effects, hole habitats showed no significant increases in macroalgal abundance (1 study) and had mixed effects on invertebrate abundance (2 studies). Pit habitats demonstrated more complex patterns with studies showing increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate abundance in some cases, but no effect or decreased abundance in others. Fish abundance and richness were only measured for pit habitats, with one study finding increases when pits were combined with grooves.\n\nBoth habitat types were used by various organisms including sea slugs, urchins, and octopuses, with pit habitats also supporting periwinkles, macroalgae, and providing feeding opportunities for fish.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3467",
    "3475",
    "3476"
  ]
}

