{
  "query": "In locations like Israel, the UK and Australia, how do outcomes vary when using environmentally-sensitive materials on subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Research on environmentally-sensitive materials on subtidal artificial structures in Israel, the UK, and Australia shows mixed outcomes. In Israel, using ECOncreteTM instead of standard-concrete, along with creating texture and habitats, altered macroalgae and invertebrate community composition and increased species diversity, but had mixed effects on fish abundance. In the UK, using recycled-cement-concrete instead of standard-concrete altered native community composition but did not increase diatom or macroalgae species richness, while shell-concrete applications increased bivalve abundance. In Australia, using shell-concrete instead of standard-concrete altered community composition but did not increase macroalgal abundance, and had mixed effects on mobile invertebrate abundance depending on species groups and sites. Across these locations, ECOncreteTM consistently increased species diversity and richness and sometimes abundance, while quarried rock and recycled-cement-concrete showed more variable results, often depending on specific sites and environmental conditions.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3470"
  ]
}

