  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating large hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures vary between subtidal zones in Israel and Sweden versus intertidal zones in Australia and Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, creating large hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures shows varying biodiversity outcomes between subtidal zones in Israel and Sweden compared to intertidal zones in Australia and Europe.\n\nSubtidal zones (Israel and Sweden): Three studies examined subtidal large hole habitats - one on an open coastline in northern Israel, one in a marina in northern Israel, and one off the west coast of Sweden. All three studies found that creating hole habitats altered the combined macroalgae and invertebrate or mobile invertebrate and fish community composition on structures, supporting species that were absent from surfaces without habitat features. Two of three studies found increased macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and/or diversity, while one found no increase in combined mobile invertebrate and fish richness. Population responses were mixed - one study reported increased brown crab abundance but not other mobile invertebrates, while macroalgae and invertebrate abundance effects varied by species group.\n\nIntertidal zones (Australia and Europe): Five studies examined intertidal large hole habitats - three in estuaries in southeast Australia and the UK, one on an open coastline in the Netherlands, and one in a marina in northern Israel. All three community response studies found that hole habitats (usually combined with other features) supported macroalgae and/or invertebrate species absent from surfaces without habitat features and increased species diversity and/or richness. Population responses were generally neutral - one study found no increase in macroalgae abundance, and two studies showed no increase in invertebrate abundance overall, though limpet abundance showed mixed effects depending on shore level and site.\n\nKey differences: Subtidal studies showed more consistent positive effects on community composition and species richness/diversity (2 of 3 studies positive) compared with intertidal studies, though all intertidal studies showed positive effects on species diversity/richness. Subtidal environments appeared to show more variable population-level responses, particularly for invertebrate abundance, while intertidal environments generally showed neutral abundance effects but consistently supported species that otherwise wouldn't colonize artificial structures.",
